<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910725-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>910725-0032.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Meritor Savings Bank:   Narrower $17 Million Loss   Is Posted for Second Period</HL><DATE>07/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MTOR</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Meritor Savings Bank, Philadelphia, reporter a sharplynarrower loss for the second quarter, though it said a highlevel of non-performing assets continues to be a drain.   The loss was $17 million, or 49 cents a share, comparedwith $136.8 million, or $3.90 a share, a year earlier.Meritor said year-earlier results were hurt by restructuringcosts and a higher provision for possible loan losses.</LP><TEXT>   In the first half, the loss narrowed to $30.4 million, or87 cents a share, from $166 million, or $4.73 a share, a yearearlier.   The company said it increased provisions for possiblecredit losses to $11 million from $5.4 million in the firstquarter and $42.5 million in year-earlier quarter.   As of June 30, total nonperforming assets amounted to $396million, close to the $399 million at March 31 and higherthan $359 million at June 30, 1990. Total assets were $6.4billion, compared with $6.5 billion at Dec. 31.</TEXT></DOC>